    <section class="mb-10">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4" id="faqAccordion">

        <div class="bg-surface rounded-xl border border-border overflow-hidden">
          <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-left hover:bg-surface-alt transition-colors">
            <span>What is the best airline miles program?</span>
            <svg class="faq-chevron w-5 h-5 text-text-muted transition-transform shrink-0" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-body hidden px-5 pb-4 text-sm text-text-muted">
            It depends on your home airport and preferred airlines. Alaska Mileage Plan and American AAdvantage consistently offer the highest value per mile at ~1.8¢ and ~1.4¢ respectively. For overall flexibility, Chase Ultimate Rewards is often considered the best transferable currency due to its breadth of transfer partners including Hyatt, United, and Southwest.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-surface rounded-xl border border-border overflow-hidden">
          <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-left hover:bg-surface-alt transition-colors">
            <span>How do I transfer credit card points to airline miles?</span>
            <svg class="faq-chevron w-5 h-5 text-text-muted transition-transform shrink-0" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-body hidden px-5 pb-4 text-sm text-text-muted">
            Most major credit card rewards programs — Chase Ultimate Rewards, Amex Membership Rewards, Capital One Miles, and Citi ThankYou Points — allow you to transfer points directly to airline and hotel loyalty programs, usually at a 1:1 ratio. Log into your credit card portal, find the "Transfer Points" section, select your airline or hotel partner, enter the amount, and the miles typically appear within minutes to a few days.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-surface rounded-xl border border-border overflow-hidden">
          <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-left hover:bg-surface-alt transition-colors">
            <span>What is the difference between airline miles and credit card points?</span>
            <svg class="faq-chevron w-5 h-5 text-text-muted transition-transform shrink-0" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-body hidden px-5 pb-4 text-sm text-text-muted">
            Airline miles are earned directly from flying or an airline co-branded credit card, and can only be redeemed within that airline's ecosystem. Credit card points (like Chase UR or Amex MR) are earned from everyday spending and offer more flexibility — you can transfer them to multiple airline and hotel programs, giving you the ability to pick the best redemption option at any time.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-surface rounded-xl border border-border overflow-hidden">
          <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-left hover:bg-surface-alt transition-colors">
            <span>Do airline miles expire?</span>
            <svg class="faq-chevron w-5 h-5 text-text-muted transition-transform shrink-0" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-body hidden px-5 pb-4 text-sm text-text-muted">
            Policies vary by program. Many programs (United, Delta, American) now have activity-based expiration — miles stay active as long as you earn or redeem within an 18–24 month window. Southwest Rapid Rewards miles never expire as long as your account is active. Alaska miles expire after 24 months of inactivity. Always check your program's current policy.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-surface rounded-xl border border-border overflow-hidden">
          <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-left hover:bg-surface-alt transition-colors">
            <span>What is the best way to redeem miles for maximum value?</span>
            <svg class="faq-chevron w-5 h-5 text-text-muted transition-transform shrink-0" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-body hidden px-5 pb-4 text-sm text-text-muted">
            The highest-value redemptions are almost always international business or first class flights, not domestic economy. For example, redeeming 70,000 Chase Ultimate Rewards points for a United business class flight to Europe (worth $3,000+) yields over 4¢ per point — far above the typical 1¢ baseline. Hotel redemptions in luxury categories (like Park Hyatt properties via World of Hyatt) also deliver exceptional value.
          </div>
        </div>

